<ArticleLayout
  title="The CRM Trap: When Systems of Record Never Become Systems of Action."
  lede="CRM only creates value when it changes how work moves, decisions get made, and outcomes are governed."
  pillar="CRM"
  date="2026"
  slug="crm-trap-systems-of-record-never-become-systems-of-action"
>
  <p>Most CRM programs do not fail because the enterprise picked the wrong platform. They fail because the platform never becomes part of how work actually moves.</p>
  <p>The system captures records. It stores activity. It gives leaders reporting. But the work still lives in email, meetings, spreadsheets, swivel-chair processes, local judgment, and informal escalation paths.</p>

  <h2>The record is not the work</h2>
  <p>A system of record tells the enterprise what happened. A system of action changes what happens next.</p>
  <p>That difference matters. If CRM does not guide the next best action, clarify ownership, support workflow, surface risk, and make follow-through easier, adoption becomes a compliance exercise.</p>

  <h2>Where value leaks</h2>
  <p>Value leaks when customer context, workflow status, decision rights, and operating controls sit in different places. The associate has one view. The advisor has another. The manager has a dashboard. The client still feels the seams.</p>
  <p>Modernization has to focus on the movement of work, not the beauty of the application.</p>

  <h2>What good looks like</h2>
  <p>CRM becomes useful when it helps the enterprise route work, prioritize action, capture evidence, reduce rework, and improve the quality of customer and associate experience.</p>
  <p>That requires data discipline, workflow design, adoption architecture, and governance. The technology matters. The operating model decides whether it matters enough.</p>

  <h2>The executive test</h2>
  <p>The question is not whether the CRM has been deployed. The question is whether it has changed how work gets done.</p>
</ArticleLayout>
